******
[1] Cholera - Southern and Eastern Africa
Date: Wed 10 Feb 2016
Source: China.org.cn, Xinhua News Agency [in Spanish trans. Corr.SB]
http://spanish.china.org.cn/international/txt/2016-02/10/content_37764511.htm


A cholera outbreak has killed more than 550 people in more than 42 000 cases reported since January 2016 in eastern and southern Africa, reported a humanitarian agency of the United Nations (UN) on 10 Feb 2016.

The UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) in eastern Africa said that outbreaks of cholera in the region in 2015 have been remarkable, both in their tendency to reappear shortly after being extinguished and in their ability to affect large geographic areas.

"Until 21 Jan 2016 [it is not entirely clear if all of these cases and deaths occurred in the 1st 3 weeks of 2016. - Mod.LL], more than 42 000 cases of cholera and more than 550 related deaths have been reported in the region," he said. The disease, which is preventable, is affecting Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, South Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda, and Zimbabwe.

OCHA said, in its latest report, that the situation in Tanzania is particularly worrisome because the disease has spread in 21 of the 30
regions of the country, including the islands of Pemba and Unguja and Zanzibar since the outbreak began in May 2015 .

The WHO notes that the main causes of cholera are the lack of clean water and sanitary conditions and inadequate facilities. WHO also he said it has increased support to respond to outbreaks of cholera in Malawi and Mozambique.

